# asumeing that we are going to fetch 400 coins that drastically incrrease procesing power isnt it?

Yes, it does matter — but let me break it down precisely so you can make an informed decision.

## Per Scan Cycle (400 coins)

|  | 120 candles | 500 candles |
| :-- | :-- | :-- |
| Total candles in memory | 48,000 | 200,000 |
| API data transferred | ~2.3 MB | ~9.6 MB |
| RSI + pivot calculations | 48,000 ops | 200,000 ops |
| **Relative load** | baseline | **~4x** |

## The Real Bottleneck

The actual bottleneck with 400 coins is **not** processing — it's the **400 API calls to Binance**. Each call has network latency regardless of whether you fetch 120 or 500 candles. The extra candles add maybe 5-10ms of parsing per coin, which is noise compared to the network round-trip.

## The Smart Solution

Instead of fetching 500 candles **every scan cycle**, you should:

- **First run** — fetch 500 candles to build the full picture
- **Subsequent runs** — fetch only the **last 2-3 candles** and append to a cached dataset

This way 400 coins × 500 candles only happens **once at startup**, then every cycle after is 400 coins × 3 candles — extremely lightweight.

